TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Two-Location Inventory Model with Transshipment and Local Decision Making
AU  - Rudi, Nils
AU  - Kapur, Sandeep
AU  - Pyke, David F.
Y1  - 2001/12/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.47.12.1668.10235
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.47.12.1668.10235
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1668
EP  - 1680
VL  - 47
IS  - 12
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In situations where a seller has surplus stock and another seller is stocked out, it may be desirable to transfer surplus stock from the former to the latter. We examine how the possibility of such transshipments between two independent locations affects the optimal inventory orders at each location. If each location aims to maximize its own profits?we call this local decision making?their inventory choices will not, in general, maximize joint profits. We find transshipment prices which induce the locations to choose inventory levels consistent with joint-profit maximization.
AB  - In situations where a seller has surplus stock and another seller is stocked out, it may be desirable to transfer surplus stock from the former to the latter. We examine how the possibility of such transshipments between two independent locations affects the optimal inventory orders at each location. If each location aims to maximize its own profits?we call this local decision making?their inventory choices will not, in general, maximize joint profits. We find transshipment prices which induce the locations to choose inventory levels consistent with joint-profit maximization.
